1.DOM XSS using web messages

Udhaifu huu wa DOM XSS hutokea kwa sababu ya kutumia .innerHTML kusindika ujumbe wa mtandao (postMessage) bila kukagua usalama wa chanzo cha ujumbe. 
Payload inatumia tag ya <img> na onerror=print() ili kukwepa ulinzi wa vivinjari na kuendesha msimbo wa JavaScript [INDEX].


labs:https://0a2a00c803f2343e807403a50067003d.web-security-academy.net/
This lab demonstrates a simple web message vulnerability. To solve this lab, 
use the exploit server to post a message to the target site that causes the print() function to be called. 
 Solution
 HII SEHEMU NDO INA WEAKNESS: [Control + U]

  <script>
                        window.addEventListener('message', function(e) {
                            document.getElementById('ads').innerHTML = e.data;
                        })
                    </script>


Msimbo (code) huu una udhaifu mkubwa wa usalama unaoitwa DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (DOM XSS) kupitia ujumbe wa mtandao (Web Messaging) .
Udhaifu huu unamruhusu mtu yeyote mbaya (hacker) kulipua au kuendesha msimbo wa JavaScript wa kijasusi kwenye kivinjari (browser) cha mtumiaji wa tovuti hii.
Hapa kuna mambo mawili makuu yanayosababisha udhaifu huu
1. Hakuna Ukaguzi wa Chanzo (Missing Origin Check)
Kosa lilipo: Msimbo unatumia window.addEventListener('message', ...) kusikiliza ujumbe, lakini haukagui ujumbe huo umetoka wapi .
Madhara yake: Tovuti yoyote ya nje au ya wadukuzi inaweza kutupa ujumbe kwa kutumia postMessage() na tovuti hii itaupokea na kuuamini bila maswali .

2. Matumizi ya .innerHTML Yasiyo SalamaKosa lilipo: Msimbo unachukua data iliyopokelewa (e.data) na kuitumbukiza moja kwa moja kwenye ukurasa kwa kutumia .innerHTML.
Madhara yake: .innerHTML inaambia kivinjari kisome data hiyo kama msimbo wa HTML . 
Mshambuliaji akituma tag za HTML kama <img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>, kivinjari kitazisoma na kuendesha JavaScript hiyo ya dharura mara moja .

  <script>
                        window.addEventListener('message', function(e) {
                            document.getElementById('ads').innerHTML = e.data;
                        })
                    </script>


  1.Notice that the home page contains an addEventListener() call that listens for a web message.
  2.Go to the exploit server and add the following iframe to the body. Remember to add your own lab ID:

  #######################################################################################################################################
   <iframe src="https://YOUR-LAB-ID.web-security-academy.net/" onload="this.contentWindow.postMessage('<img src=1 onerror=print()>','*')">
  ########################################################################################################################################

  eg. <iframe src="https://0a2a00c803f2343e807403a50067003d.web-security-academy.net/" onload="this.contentWindow.postMessage('<img src=1 onerror=print()>','*')">
  3.Store the exploit and deliver it to the victim.


When the iframe loads, the postMessage() method sends a web message to the home page. 
The event listener, which is intended to serve ads, takes the content of the web message and inserts it into the div with the ID ads. 
However, 
in this case it inserts our img tag, which contains an invalid src attribute. 
This throws an error, which causes the onerror event handler to execute our payload. 


PREVETION:
<script>
